# Go Code Rules — BundleIQ

## Package Structure
- `internal/` packages are not importable externally — keep business logic here
- `main.go` only does: parse config, initialize dependencies, start server
- No circular imports. Dependency direction: `server` → `analysis` → `bundle` → (stdlib only)

## Error Handling (non-negotiable)
```go
// CORRECT
result, err := doSomething(ctx)
if err != nil {
    return fmt.Errorf("doSomething: %w", err)
}

// WRONG — never do this
result, _ := doSomething(ctx)

// WRONG — too vague
if err != nil {
    return err
}
```
- Always wrap errors with `fmt.Errorf("functionName: %w", err)`
- Use `errors.Is()` and `errors.As()` for error type checking, never string matching

## Context Usage
```go
// CORRECT — context first, always
func Parse(ctx context.Context, dir string) (*BundleData, error) {
    select {
    case <-ctx.Done():
        return nil, ctx.Err()
    default:
    }
    // ... work ...
}

// WRONG — no context on I/O functions
func Parse(dir string) (*BundleData, error) { ... }
```
- Check `ctx.Done()` at the start of long loops

## Concurrency
```go
// CORRECT — RWMutex pattern for session store
type Store struct {
    mu       sync.RWMutex
    sessions map[string]*Session
}

func (s *Store) Get(id string) (*Session, bool) {
    s.mu.RLock()
    defer s.mu.RUnlock()
    sess, ok := s.sessions[id]
    return sess, ok
}

func (s *Store) Set(id string, sess *Session) {
    s.mu.Lock()
    defer s.mu.Unlock()
    s.sessions[id] = sess
}
```
- Always `defer mu.Unlock()` immediately after `mu.Lock()`
- Never hold a lock while doing I/O

## SSE Pattern (copy exactly)
```go
func (h *Handler) HandleSSEStream(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
    flusher, ok := w.(http.Flusher)
    if !ok {
        http.Error(w, "streaming not supported", http.StatusInternalServerError)
        return
    }
    
    w.Header().Set("Content-Type", "text/event-stream")
    w.Header().Set("Cache-Control", "no-cache")
    w.Header().Set("Connection", "keep-alive")
    w.Header().Set("X-Accel-Buffering", "no")
    
    ctx := r.Context()
    
    // Start work in goroutine, communicate via channel
    ch := make(chan string, 10)
    errCh := make(chan error, 1)
    go func() {
        err := doWork(ctx, ch)
        errCh <- err
        close(ch)
    }()
    
    for {
        select {
        case <-ctx.Done():
            return  // client disconnected — goroutine will exit via ctx
        case chunk, ok := <-ch:
            if !ok {
                fmt.Fprintf(w, "event: done\ndata: {}\n\n")
                flusher.Flush()
                return
            }
            fmt.Fprintf(w, "event: chunk\ndata: %s\n\n", chunk)
            flusher.Flush()
        }
    }
}
```

## HTTP Handlers
```go
// Route params: use r.PathValue("id") (Go 1.22+ stdlib routing)
sessionID := r.PathValue("sessionID")

// Method routing in Go 1.22+
mux.HandleFunc("POST /upload", h.HandleUpload)
mux.HandleFunc("GET /stream/{sessionID}/triage", h.HandleTriageSSE)

// Always set Content-Type before writing body
w.Header().Set("Content-Type", "application/json")
w.WriteHeader(http.StatusBadRequest)
json.NewEncoder(w).Encode(map[string]string{"error": "file too large"})
```

## File I/O Safety
```go
// CORRECT — streaming tar extraction
gr, err := gzip.NewReader(r)
if err != nil {
    return "", fmt.Errorf("gzip.NewReader: %w", err)
}
defer gr.Close()
tr := tar.NewReader(gr)

// CORRECT — path traversal prevention
cleanPath := filepath.Clean(header.Name)
if strings.Contains(cleanPath, "..") {
    continue // skip malicious paths
}

// CORRECT — size limit per file
const maxFileSize = 50 * 1024 * 1024 // 50MB
lr := io.LimitReader(tr, maxFileSize+1)
n, err := io.Copy(dst, lr)
if n > maxFileSize {
    return "", fmt.Errorf("file %s exceeds 50MB limit", header.Name)
}
```

## JSON Handling
```go
// CORRECT — strict JSON decode with DisallowUnknownFields for our own types
// But lenient for K8s API objects (they have many fields we don't care about)
var pods corev1.PodList
if err := json.Unmarshal(data, &pods); err != nil {
    // Log but don't fatal — bundle files can have edge cases
    data.ParseErrors = append(data.ParseErrors, fmt.Sprintf("pods.json: %v", err))
    return
}

// CORRECT — always check for nil before accessing nested K8s fields
if pod.Status.ContainerStatuses != nil {
    for _, cs := range pod.Status.ContainerStatuses {
        if cs.State.Waiting != nil {
            reason = cs.State.Waiting.Reason
        }
    }
}
```

## Constants and Configuration
```go
// CORRECT — named constants for all magic numbers
const (
    maxBundleSizeMB  = 250
    maxFileSizeMB    = 50
    maxTotalSizeMB   = 500
    maxTokenBudget   = 80_000
    maxLogLines      = 50
    maxLogContainers = 10
    sessionTTL       = 30 * time.Minute
    cacheTTL         = 2 * time.Hour
)

// WRONG — magic numbers inline
if size > 250*1024*1024 { ... }
```

## Template Rendering
```go
// CORRECT — parse templates once at startup, store on handler
type Handler struct {
    tmpl *template.Template
    // ...
}

// In main.go / setup:
tmpl := template.Must(template.ParseGlob("templates/**/*.html"))

// In handler:
if err := h.tmpl.ExecuteTemplate(w, "report.html", data); err != nil {
    // Log the error — ExecuteTemplate may have already written partial response
    slog.Error("template execution failed", "err", err)
}
```

## Logging
```go
// Use slog (stdlib, Go 1.21+)
import "log/slog"

slog.Info("bundle extracted", "sessionID", id, "files", fileCount, "bytes", totalBytes)
slog.Error("analysis failed", "sessionID", id, "phase", "triage", "err", err)
slog.Warn("token budget enforced", "before", before, "after", after)

// NEVER use fmt.Println for production logging
// NEVER log sensitive data (API keys, user content)
```

## Testing
```go
// Table-driven tests always
func TestExtract(t *testing.T) {
    tests := []struct{
        name    string
        input   []byte
        wantErr bool
        wantFiles int
    }{
        {"valid tar.gz", makeTarGz(t, ...),  false, 3},
        {"path traversal", makeEvilTar(t, ...), true, 0},
        {"empty archive", makeEmpty(t), false, 0},
    }
    for _, tt := range tests {
        t.Run(tt.name, func(t *testing.T) {
            dir, err := Extract(context.Background(), bytes.NewReader(tt.input), 100<<20)
            if (err != nil) != tt.wantErr {
                t.Errorf("Extract() error = %v, wantErr %v", err, tt.wantErr)
            }
            // ...
        })
    }
}
```
